# Qwen 3.5 AI Agent — Empirically-Tuned Configuration
# IMPORTANT: Qwen 3.5 behaves very differently from Gemma 4. Do not copy
# the Gemma 4 parameters (especially temperature) onto this model.
#
# Usage:
#   ollama create qwen35-agent -f ./qwen35-agent.Modelfile
#   ollama run qwen35-agent
#
# Replace the FROM line below with your actual local model tag.

FROM qwen3.5:latest

# =============================================================================
# INFERENCE PARAMETERS — Qwen 3.5 specific.
# These differ significantly from Gemma 4. Source: community testing + docs.
# =============================================================================

# Qwen 3.5 does NOT need temperature 1.0. That was a Gemma 4 quirk.
# For agentic coding with thinking mode enabled, 0.6 gives deterministic,
# reproducible reasoning chains. For general agent tasks, 0.7 is safer.
# Never use greedy decoding (temp 0.0) — output quality degrades badly.
PARAMETER temperature 0.7

# Higher top_p for thinking mode (0.95). Lower for non-thinking (0.8).
# If your framework disables thinking, drop this to 0.8.
PARAMETER top_p 0.95

# Qwen 3.5 default. Community consensus: leave at 20.
PARAMETER top_k 20

# Lower than Gemma 4's 1.1. Qwen 3.5 is more sensitive to repeat penalty.
# 1.0 lets the model repeat when necessary (tool schemas, reasoning steps).
# 1.05 is the max for coding agents without breaking coherence.
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.0

# Qwen 3.5 has a 262K native context window but Ollama performance is poor
# at full length. 24GB VRAM → 16384. 32GB+ → 32768. 48GB+ → 65536.
# Do not blindly set 262K — you will OOM or hit the thinking-loop bug.
PARAMETER num_ctx 32768

# =============================================================================
# SYSTEM PROMPT — INTENTIONALLY LEFT EMPTY
# =============================================================================
#
# WARNING: Do NOT add a fixed SYSTEM prompt here.
# Qwen 3.5's native chat template handles thinking mode, tool calling,
# and reasoning structure. Overriding the template or hardcoding a SYSTEM
# block breaks tool calling and can trigger infinite chain-of-thought loops
# in Ollama (issue #14493, #14809).
#
# Let your agent framework inject the system prompt dynamically per-turn.
# This is the exact opposite of the Gemma 4 strategy, where the fixed SYSTEM
# prompt helped prevent context collapse.
#
# If you need a no-think variant, see:
#   https://ollama.com/frob/qwen3.5-instruct
# (Ollama does not yet support PARAMETER think false natively.)

# =============================================================================
# TEMPLATE — INTENTIONALLY NOT OVERRIDDEN
# =============================================================================
#
# Do NOT add a custom TEMPLATE block. Qwen 3.5's GGUF contains the correct
# Jinja template with thinking-mode tags and tool-calling XML formatting.
# Ollama's template override has been the root cause of broken tool use.
#
# If you are sideloading a raw GGUF that lacks template metadata, pull the
# official Ollama model first and diff the templates, or use llama.cpp directly.

# =============================================================================
# KNOWN OLLAMA ISSUES (as of early 2026)
# =============================================================================
# - Tool calling is broken in Ollama for Qwen 3.5 (issue #14493).
#   If your agent relies on native Ollama tool_call, use llama.cpp server
#   or vLLM instead until patches land (typically 2-4 weeks post-release).
# - Thinking mode cannot be disabled via Modelfile (issue #14809).
#   Workaround: pass "think: false" in the API request body, or use the
#   frob/qwen3.5-instruct community model.
# - Speed: Ollama is 5-7x slower than llama.cpp for the same Qwen 3.5 GGUF.
# - Vision (mmproj) files are not bundled in Ollama releases.
#
# Recommended inference backends for Qwen 3.5 agents:
#   1. llama.cpp server (best single-GPU stability)
#   2. vLLM (best for serving / multi-user)
#   3. MLX (best for Apple Silicon)
#
# If you must use Ollama, keep the Modelfile minimal (like this one)
# and handle all tool orchestration in your application layer.
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# WHEN TO ADJUST PARAMETERS
# =============================================================================
# | Mode           | Temperature | Top_P | Repeat Penalty | Notes          |
# |----------------|-------------|-------|----------------|----------------|
# | Thinking/Coding| 0.6         | 0.95  | 1.0            | Deterministic  |
# | General Agent  | 0.7         | 0.95  | 1.0            | Balanced       |
# | Non-thinking   | 0.7         | 0.8   | 1.05           | Faster, direct |
# | Creative       | 1.0         | 0.95  | 1.5            | Exploration    |
#
# If you need a dual-mode setup, create two model variants:
#   ollama create qwen35-agent-think  -f ./qwen35-agent.Modelfile
#   ollama create qwen35-agent-fast   -f ./qwen35-agent-fast.Modelfile
# =============================================================================
